---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "15 Best Undervalued Stocks for 2025 | Westmount Fundamentals",
  description: "Are market indices hiding incredible bargains? We ran the numbers to find deeply discounted cash cows poised for a potential rebound. See our top picks.",
  category: "list",
  published: "2024-06-10",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": meta.title,
      "description": meta.description,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals"
      },
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals",
        "logo": {
          "@type": "ImageObject",
          "url": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/logo.png"
        }
      },
      "datePublished": meta.published
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What makes a stock undervalued?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A stock is considered undervalued when it trades for less than its intrinsic value. This is often measured using metrics like the Price-to-Earnings (P/E) ratio, Price-to-Book (P/B), or Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) models compared to historical averages or peers."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why do stocks become undervalued?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Stocks can become undervalued due to temporary bad news, broader market corrections, cyclical industry downturns, or simply because they are overlooked by investors chasing high-growth sectors."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How long does it take for an undervalued stock to recover?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "It varies wildly. A recovery requires a 'catalyst'—like an earnings beat, a change in management, a macro-economic shift, or a buyout offer. This can take months or sometimes years, testing an investor's patience."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is a 'value trap'?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A value trap is a stock that looks cheap based on traditional metrics (like a low P/E ratio) but is actually cheap for a very good reason—such as declining revenues, obsolete technology, or crippling debt. The stock price never recovers."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Are undervalued stocks safer than growth stocks?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Not necessarily. While undervalued stocks theoretically have a 'margin of safety' because they are already beaten down, they often face significant business challenges. However, they generally experience less volatility than high-multiple growth stocks."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/best-undervalued-stocks-2025" schema={JSON.stringify(schema)}>
  <div class="page-content container">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>15 Best Undervalued Stocks for 2025</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Looking past the mega-cap tech rally, we analyzed the market for companies trading at extreme discounts to their intrinsic value, cash flow, and historical averages.</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>The Search for Asymmetric Upside</h2>
      <p>
        In recent years, market returns have been heavily concentrated in a handful of mega-cap technology stocks. While momentum has driven those names to premium valuations, it has simultaneously created a deep bifurcated market where many traditional, cash-generating businesses have been left behind.
      </p>
      <p>
        For value investors, this represents a classic setup. When a stock is "undervalued," it means it is currently trading for less than its perceived intrinsic value—often measured by metrics like Price-to-Earnings (P/E), Price-to-Book (P/B), or Free Cash Flow (FCF) yield relative to its peers or historical averages.
      </p>
      <p>
        However, the key to successful value investing is avoiding "value traps"—stocks that are cheap for a very good reason, such as dying industries or crippling debt. The list below highlights 15 stocks across various sectors that are deeply discounted, possess strong underlying fundamentals, and have visible catalysts for a re-rating in 2025 and beyond. For targeted commodity exposure, don't miss our analysis of the <a href="/best-uranium-stocks" style="color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: underline;">best uranium stocks</a>, or if you prefer trading lower-priced equities, see our list of the <a href="/best-cheap-stocks-to-buy-now" style="color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: underline;">best cheap stocks under $20</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Undervalued Stocks Comparison Table</h2>
      <p>Use the table below to compare the top undervalued stocks by sector, forward P/E ratio, and dividend yield.</p>

      <div class="filter-controls">
        <label for="sector-filter">Filter by Sector:</label>
        <select id="sector-filter">
          <option value="all">All Sectors</option>
          <option value="Financials">Financials</option>
          <option value="Healthcare">Healthcare</option>
          <option value="Energy">Energy</option>
          <option value="Consumer">Consumer</option>
          <option value="Industrials">Industrials</option>
          <option value="Technology">Technology</option>
        </select>
      </div>

      <div class="table-container">
        <table id="value-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th data-sort="rank">Rank ↕</th>
              <th data-sort="ticker">Ticker ↕</th>
              <th data-sort="company">Company ↕</th>
              <th data-sort="sector">Sector ↕</th>
              <th data-sort="pe">Fwd P/E ↕</th>
              <th data-sort="yield">Div Yield ↕</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr data-sector="Financials">
              <td>1</td><td>BAC</td><td>Bank of America Corp.</td><td>Financials</td><td>10.5x</td><td>2.8%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Healthcare">
              <td>2</td><td>PFE</td><td>Pfizer Inc.</td><td>Healthcare</td><td>11.2x</td><td>6.1%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Energy">
              <td>3</td><td>CVX</td><td>Chevron Corp.</td><td>Energy</td><td>11.8x</td><td>4.2%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Consumer">
              <td>4</td><td>TGT</td><td>Target Corp.</td><td>Consumer</td><td>15.5x</td><td>3.1%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Industrials">
              <td>5</td><td>DE</td><td>Deere & Company</td><td>Industrials</td><td>14.0x</td><td>1.5%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Healthcare">
              <td>6</td><td>CVS</td><td>CVS Health Corp.</td><td>Healthcare</td><td>8.5x</td><td>3.8%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Financials">
              <td>7</td><td>C</td><td>Citigroup Inc.</td><td>Financials</td><td>8.8x</td><td>3.5%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Technology">
              <td>8</td><td>INTC</td><td>Intel Corp.</td><td>Technology</td><td>20.5x</td><td>1.4%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Energy">
              <td>9</td><td>DVN</td><td>Devon Energy</td><td>Energy</td><td>8.2x</td><td>5.5%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Consumer">
              <td>10</td><td>WBA</td><td>Walgreens Boots Alliance</td><td>Consumer</td><td>6.5x</td><td>4.8%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Industrials">
              <td>11</td><td>LUV</td><td>Southwest Airlines</td><td>Industrials</td><td>15.0x</td><td>2.5%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Healthcare">
              <td>12</td><td>BMY</td><td>Bristol-Myers Squibb</td><td>Healthcare</td><td>7.2x</td><td>5.8%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Consumer">
              <td>13</td><td>SBUX</td><td>Starbucks Corp.</td><td>Consumer</td><td>21.0x</td><td>2.6%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Energy">
              <td>14</td><td>BKR</td><td>Baker Hughes Co.</td><td>Energy</td><td>14.5x</td><td>2.5%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr data-sector="Financials">
              <td>15</td><td>USB</td><td>U.S. Bancorp</td><td>Financials</td><td>11.0x</td><td>4.5%</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="ranked-list">
      <h2>The Top 15 Undervalued Opportunities</h2>

      <div class="card" id="rank-1">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">1</div>
          <h3>Bank of America Corp. (BAC)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Financials</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~10.5x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          As the second-largest U.S. bank, Bank of America suffered a significant valuation multiple contraction during the regional banking crisis, despite its massive, highly sticky deposit base. While higher interest rates caused paper losses on their held-to-maturity bond portfolio, their Net Interest Income (NII) remains incredibly robust. Trading at essentially its tangible book value, BAC represents an asymmetric setup for long-term investors as interest rates normalize and bond portfolios roll off.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Massive, low-cost deposit franchise.</li>
              <li>Trading near Tangible Book Value (TBV).</li>
              <li>Strong history of dividend growth and share repurchases.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Large unrealized losses on HTM bond portfolios limit short-term flexibility.</li>
              <li>Highly sensitive to a potential macroeconomic recession.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-2">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">2</div>
          <h3>Pfizer Inc. (PFE)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Healthcare</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~11.2x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Pfizer experienced a massive boom in revenue during the COVID-19 pandemic, followed by a severe hangover as vaccine and Paxlovid sales normalized faster than the market expected. The stock was punished relentlessly. However, the company used its pandemic windfall to make significant acquisitions, padding its pipeline for the next decade. At a high-single-digit P/E and a massive dividend yield over 6%, the market is pricing in zero growth, providing a tremendous margin of safety.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Highly defensive, counter-cyclical healthcare business.</li>
              <li>Massive +6% dividend yield supported by operating cash flow.</li>
              <li>Recent acquisitions (like Seagen) bolster long-term oncology pipeline.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Several key patents are expiring over the next 5 years (the "patent cliff").</li>
              <li>Near-term earnings comps remain difficult due to lingering COVID revenues.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-3">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">3</div>
          <h3>Chevron Corp. (CVX)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Energy</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~11.8x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Energy stocks broadly remain undervalued relative to the S&P 500. Chevron, a premier global supermajor, boasts a fortress balance sheet and an exceptionally low breakeven cost for its oil production. With its massive Permian Basin footprint and pending acquisition of Hess Corporation, Chevron is positioned to generate massive free cash flow even if oil prices stagnate. It trades at a steep discount to historical multiples despite structurally higher capital discipline.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Extremely strong balance sheet with low net debt.</li>
              <li>Aggressive share buyback program returning massive capital to shareholders.</li>
              <li>Top-tier assets in the Permian Basin.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Highly correlated to the underlying price of crude oil.</li>
              <li>Regulatory scrutiny surrounding the Hess acquisition.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-4">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">4</div>
          <h3>Target Corp. (TGT)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Consumer Discretionary</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~15.5x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Target suffered from a confluence of issues: inventory bloat post-pandemic, shrink (theft), and a consumer pullback in discretionary spending. This drove margins to historic lows and the stock price down alongside them. However, Target has aggressively cleared inventory and rightsized its cost structure. As margins normalize to historical averages, the earnings leverage is significant, making the current valuation highly attractive.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Strong omnichannel retail strategy and loyal customer base.</li>
              <li>Dividend Aristocrat status with decades of consecutive increases.</li>
              <li>Significant margin expansion potential as inventory issues clear.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Vulnerable to consumer spending slowdowns, unlike defensive peers like Walmart.</li>
              <li>Ongoing struggles with retail shrink (theft) impacting margins.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-5">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">5</div>
          <h3>Deere & Company (DE)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Industrials</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~14.0x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Deere is transitioning from a traditional heavy machinery manufacturer to an agricultural technology company. Their investments in autonomous tractors and precision agriculture software are creating recurring, high-margin revenue streams. Despite this transformation, the stock frequently trades at a cyclical discount when crop prices dip. At ~14x forward earnings, investors are getting a world-class, moated business at a very reasonable price.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Dominant market share in North American agriculture equipment.</li>
              <li>Rapidly growing, high-margin software and precision tech revenues.</li>
              <li>Excellent capital allocation and return on invested capital (ROIC).</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Highly cyclical business tied to farm incomes and crop prices.</li>
              <li>Higher interest rates make equipment financing more expensive for farmers.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-6">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">6</div>
          <h3>CVS Health Corp. (CVS)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Healthcare</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~8.5x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Trading at just 8.5x earnings, CVS has been severely punished by rising medical costs in its Aetna insurance division and a sluggish retail pharmacy segment. However, its integrated healthcare model generates massive free cash flow, supporting a nearly 4% dividend while management executes a turnaround.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Massive free cash flow generation.</li>
              <li>Vertically integrated across pharmacy, PBM, and insurance.</li>
              <li>Secure, high-yield dividend while waiting for turnaround.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Struggling retail pharmacy segment facing theft and margin pressure.</li>
              <li>Medicare Advantage cost pressures hurting Aetna division.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-7">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">7</div>
          <h3>Citigroup Inc. (C)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Financials</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~8.8x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          The ultimate deep-value turnaround play in banking. Citigroup trades well below its tangible book value. CEO Jane Fraser is executing a massive, multi-year restructuring to simplify the bank and improve returns. If she succeeds, the upside re-rating is massive.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Trading at a steep discount to tangible book value.</li>
              <li>Massive, globally dominant Treasury and Trade Solutions (TTS) business.</li>
              <li>Aggressive divestiture of underperforming consumer units.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Turnaround is complex and will take years to fully execute.</li>
              <li>Historical execution issues continue to weigh on investor sentiment.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-8">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">8</div>
          <h3>Intel Corp. (INTC)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Technology</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~20.5x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Intel is executing one of the most complex corporate turnarounds in history, attempting to regain process leadership from TSMC while building a massive foundry business. It carries high execution risk, but at current valuations, the market is pricing in near-total failure, offering tremendous upside if they execute.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Massive government support (CHIPS Act) for domestic manufacturing.</li>
              <li>Still generates billions in cash flow from legacy PC/Server business.</li>
              <li>Market expectations are extremely low, creating an asymmetric setup.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Losing market share to AMD in data centers.</li>
              <li>Building a leading-edge foundry is incredibly capital intensive.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-9">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">9</div>
          <h3>Devon Energy (DVN)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Energy</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~8.2x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Devon pioneered the fixed-plus-variable dividend framework in the E&P sector. Despite incredible capital discipline and top-tier assets in the Delaware Basin, the stock trades at a low single-digit free cash flow multiple, deeply undervaluing its long-term cash generation capabilities.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Shareholder-friendly capital return program (dividends + buybacks).</li>
              <li>High-quality, low-breakeven acreage in key US basins.</li>
              <li>Trading at a very low free cash flow multiple.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Variable dividend means payouts drop when oil prices fall.</li>
              <li>Highly sensitive to underlying commodity prices.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-10">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">10</div>
          <h3>Walgreens Boots Alliance (WBA)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Consumer Discretionary</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~6.5x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Walgreens is a controversial deep-value play. After slashing its dividend, the stock plummeted to multi-decade lows. The turnaround under new management is arduous, but at ~6x earnings, any stabilization in the core pharmacy business could double the stock price.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Valuation is completely washed out; extremely low bar for success.</li>
              <li>New management focused on core pharmacy operations.</li>
              <li>Massive retail footprint provides a baseline of recurring revenue.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>High debt load complicates the turnaround effort.</li>
              <li>Severe margin pressure from pharmacy benefit managers (PBMs).</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-11">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">11</div>
          <h3>Southwest Airlines (LUV)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Industrials</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~15.0x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          After a high-profile operational meltdown and activist investor pressure, Southwest is restructuring its route network and ending its famous open-seating policy to drive premium revenue. Trading at multi-year lows, it remains one of the few airlines with an investment-grade balance sheet.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Investment-grade balance sheet in a capital-intensive industry.</li>
              <li>Activist pressure is forcing long-overdue modernization (assigned seating).</li>
              <li>Extremely loyal customer base.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Airline industry is notoriously cyclical and low-margin.</li>
              <li>Execution risk transitioning away from their 50-year open seating model.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-12">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">12</div>
          <h3>Bristol-Myers Squibb (BMY)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Healthcare</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~7.2x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Facing the patent cliffs of its two blockbuster drugs (Revlimid and Eliquis), BMY has been severely discounted to just 7x earnings. However, the market is undervaluing its recent string of successful drug launches and acquisitions, providing a near 6% yield while investors wait for the new portfolio to ramp up.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>High dividend yield provides income during the transition period.</li>
              <li>Recent acquisitions pad the long-term pipeline.</li>
              <li>Extremely low valuation multiple limits further downside risk.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Significant revenue loss expected from impending patent expirations.</li>
              <li>Recent acquisitions increased the debt load.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-13">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">13</div>
          <h3>Starbucks Corp. (SBUX)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Consumer Discretionary</p>
          <p><strong>Fwd P/E:</strong> ~21.0x</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Hit by sluggish US traffic and an intense price war in China, Starbucks' valuation has compressed significantly. However, under new leadership (Brian Niccol, formerly of Chipotle), the company has a clear mandate to return to its roots as a premium coffeehouse, making the current valuation a compelling entry point for a global brand.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>One of the strongest consumer brands globally.</li>
              <li>New CEO has a proven track record of successful retail turnarounds.</li>
              <li>Strong loyalty program drives recurring digital revenue.</li>
