    <section>
      <h2>Ranking Methodology</h2>
      <p>
        Identifying true undervalued opportunities requires looking beyond just a low P/E ratio. Our methodology focuses on identifying "quality value" rather than value traps. We prioritize:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Historical Valuation Averages:</strong> We compare a company's current valuation metrics (P/E, P/B, EV/EBITDA) against its own 5-year and 10-year historical averages.</li>
        <li><strong>Free Cash Flow Yield:</strong> Earnings can be manipulated by accounting practices, but cash is king. We favor companies generating robust, recurring free cash flow relative to their enterprise value.</li>
        <li><strong>Balance Sheet Strength:</strong> Undervalued companies often face temporary operational headwinds. A strong balance sheet ensures they have the runway to execute a turnaround without facing a liquidity crisis.</li>
        <li><strong>Catalyst Identification:</strong> A cheap stock can stay cheap forever without a catalyst. We look for tangible events—like new management, a cyclical industry bottom, or a strategic restructuring—that can unlock shareholder value.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What makes a stock undervalued?</summary>
        <p>
          A stock is considered undervalued when it trades for less than its intrinsic value. This is often measured using metrics like the Price-to-Earnings (P/E) ratio, Price-to-Book (P/B), or Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) models compared to historical averages or peers.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why do stocks become undervalued?</summary>
        <p>
          Stocks can become undervalued due to temporary bad news, broader market corrections, cyclical industry downturns, or simply because they are overlooked by investors chasing high-growth sectors.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How long does it take for an undervalued stock to recover?</summary>
        <p>
          It varies wildly. A recovery requires a "catalyst"—like an earnings beat, a change in management, a macro-economic shift, or a buyout offer. This can take months or sometimes years, testing an investor's patience.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is a "value trap"?</summary>
        <p>
          A value trap is a stock that looks cheap based on traditional metrics (like a low P/E ratio) but is actually cheap for a very good reason—such as declining revenues, obsolete technology, or crippling debt. The stock price never recovers.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Are undervalued stocks safer than growth stocks?</summary>
        <p>
          Not necessarily. While undervalued stocks theoretically have a "margin of safety" because they are already beaten down, they often face significant business challenges. However, they generally experience less volatility than high-multiple growth stocks.
        </p>
      </details>
    </section>
